{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"88"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"88","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/88"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.23,0.35,0.06,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"88"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110559"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"88","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/88"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"88"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"2852"},{"type":"tags","id":"2860"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4298"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1622"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42966"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110559"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of severe pain, erythema and swelling of his right ankle. There is no recent history of trauma or infection. The patient has a background of end-stage kidney disease with a recent creatinine clearance (CrCL) of \u0026lt; 30 mL/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing a thorough physical examination, arthrocentesis and analysis of the fluid are performed. The results showed needle-shaped, negatively birefringent crystals on microscopy and no evidence of infection on gram stain and culture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral indomethacin","Colchicine","Intra-articular corticosteroid","Allopurinol","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s clinical presentation and investigation findings are diagnostic of acute gout including the presence of an acute monoarticular arthritis and the presence of negative-birefringent needle-shaped crystals in the synovial fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of treatment options for acute gout episodes including; oral non-steroidal anti-inflammatories (NSAIDs), steroids (intra-articular or oral), and low dose colchicine. The choice of treatment option is dependent on the patient\u0027s risk factors including kidney function. Current consensus recommends the use of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintra-articular corticosteroid \u003C/strong\u003Einjections for patients with end-stage chronic kidney disease due to the risk of adverse effects associated especially with NSAIDs and the difficulty in dose-adjusting colchicine at CrCLs of less than 30 mL/min. As this patient has already had an arthrocentesis, they are likely to tolerate an intra-articular steroid, which remains the optimal option, if it is available. The decision of IA steroid versus systemic corticosteroids is also influenced by time pressure, clinician familiarity with joint injections, availability of intra-articular steroids, patient preference, and likely tolerability depending on the joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone \u003C/strong\u003Eis appropriate for polyarticular gout flares in patients with CKD but intra-articular steroids are still preferred for monoarticular flares in an accessible joint with no contraindication to injection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral indomethacin\u003C/strong\u003E is an NSAID that is appropriate for the management of acute gout in patients with normal kidney function but not chronic kidney disease or a risk of developing an acute kidney injury. Therefore, this option is not appropriate for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColchicine\u003C/strong\u003E may be used safely in chronic kidney disease without dose-adjustment for patients with a CrCL \u2265 30 mL/min. This patient\u0027s low GFR necessitates dose-adjustment of colchicine where there still remains some risk. Therefore \u0022...when considering kidney safety, glucocorticoids may be the safest option for patients with CKD, remaining highly effective regardless of flare duration.\u0022\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllopurinol i\u003C/strong\u003Es used in the long-term management of gout and does not have a role in the \u003Cem\u003Esymptomatic \u003C/em\u003Emanagement of an acute flare. For long-term management, this patient would benefit from urate-lowering therapy (such as allopurinol), which can be started during an acute attack (a common misconception) as this does not prolong the flare. Treatment should aim for a serum urate target below 0.36 mmol/L, or below 0.30 mmol/L in those with tophi. When initiating urate-lowering therapy, prophylactic anti-inflammatory medication (low-dose colchicine or NSAIDs if not contraindicated) should be prescribed for at least 3-6 months to prevent flares that commonly occur during the initial phase of urate-lowering therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The management of acute gout is influenced by the presence of chronic kidney disease.","In patients with end-stage CKD (CrCL \u003C 30 mL/min), intra-articular corticosteroid injections are often preferred as first-line management."],"references":["Dalbeth N, Merriman TR, Stamp LK. Gout. Lancet 2016; 388:2039-52.","Vargas-Santos A, Neogi T. Management of Gout and Hyperuricemia in CKD. American Journal of Kidney Diseases. 2017;70(3):422-439.","Robinson PC, Stamp LK. The management of gout: Much has changed. Aust Fam Physician. 2016 May;45(5):299-302. PMID: 27166465. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/may/the-management-of-gout-much-has-changed"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92816"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"88"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92816"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T15:00:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T15:00:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"88"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110559"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou